<br>
First, I'd like to tell you a little about where I'm coming from on this.  I have been a Christian my whole life, raised Catholic (though my parents were pretty non-religious) and joining a Lutheran ELCA church several years ago.  There have always been things about Christianity that have bothered me, and I have done much reading and studying on the subject.  Basically, I still have a lot of problems with the Bible and would *love* if someone could logically explain the contradictions and ethical problems I have with it.  I don't approach my studies as a way to dismiss the Bible, but rather to confirm it as some source of truth in my life--and so far that has not happened.  Everything I learn causes more doubt and confusion, and I often wonder why I stick with this religion.  But I do, and I'm still searching for answers.<br>
<br>
So, that's a little background on me.  I read the transcript of the debate between the apologist and Till, and I have to say I thought Till won that one big time (though there was obviously an audience hostile to him, from the notes about applause and reactions).  Basically, it seemed that his (the apologist--sorry I can't remember his name!) argument was that Jesus died and rose from the dead because the Bible said so.  He claims the Bible is believable because it was accurately copied so many times over a long period and provided eyewitness testimony of trustworthy people.  (How does he know these people were trustworthy?)  And I believe his other argument went something like, &quot;Well, you can't prove it didn't happen.&quot;  He didn't address any of the valid arguments brought up by Till, like:  How does something being copied accurately make it true?  (I'm sure the Qu'ran has been accurately copied for centuries--does that make it true?)  What about the Book of Mormon?  (No offense to Mormons here--this was part of Till's argument).  There were several reported eyewitnesses to these golden tablets.  Why do you (the apologist) not accept that as God's truth, if eyewitness accounts are acceptable proof?  What about the fact that almost all Biblical scholars agree that the gospels were NOT written by the disciples bearing their names and were not eyewitness accounts?  I have done a ton of reading about this, and it seems that a handful of fundamentalist scholars insist on Matthew, Mark, Luke, and John being the actual authors, but the arguments for this not being the case are overwhelming from a historical standpoint.  I'm not talking about skeptics trying to discredit the Bible, I'm talking about Christian scholars as well.  And if it is indeed not eyewitness testimony, his whole argument falls apart.  In his final statement, he said something like, &quot;What's the harm in believing?  If you're right, you receive eternal life.&quot;  I have to ask, exactly what kind of faith is that?  Are you *really* a believer if you have that attitude? (Gee, this doesn't make any sense, but I'll pretend it does just in case there's a hell).  And I have to agree with DBC's statement that since the Bible clearly was trying to further a cause, it is logical to not consider it a historical source on par with others which merely sought to record history.  I'm not saying it's NOT historical--just that by its purpose and nature it's reasonable to be more skeptical about it.<br>
<br>
As I've said, I am a Christian and I really wanted to be convinced by this guy...but I wasn't, not even a little.  I thought Till by far made the more logical arguments.  Maybe this is just a matter of faith, and either you have it or you don't.  I'm just not the kind of person who can make myself believe something that doesn't make sense to me, you know?  I started reading the Paul link but it was so long and I didn't have time...having read &quot;The Mythmaker&quot; I am really interested in what it has to say, so I'll try to read it later.  <br>
<br>
I don't mean any of this in any negative way toward you, Candy, I appreciate your efforts in this area.  I still need a lot more convincing, and I really want to see both sides of this.  So...got anything else? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Thanks,<br>
