&quot;As far as the debate link…people tend to forget that any good apologist will not debate for the sake of simply “winning” …apologists are not out to win, only to give a reasonable defense.&quot; <br>
<br>
That's my problem, though--I didn't really see a reasonable defense, I saw someone who passionately believes in the Bible say that it's true without any convincing evidence.  If you want to say it's a matter of faith, that's fine--I just don't think there's much point in trying to debate the subject without facts. <br>
<br>
<br>
&quot;The reason for Christians to deny the Qu’ran as scripture is that specifically it denies the deity of Christ and his death on the cross as the atonement…those are pretty central teachings of the New Testaments. There is no particularly good reason to accept it as inspired scripture. He may have even been a particularly holy man and profound teacher, but we, as Christians, can’t accept his recitations as inspired over the NT, especially when one believes that Jesus authenticated his claims of divinity with His resurrection.&quot;<br>
<br>
I understand this argument, but it presupposes the validity of the Bible.  The apologist had argued that the Bible had been accurately copied from its original form over many centuries, and that was suppose to be an argument for its accuracy.  My point was that the Qu'ran had also been accurately copied (according to Muslims, much more accurately than the Bible...this is one of their arguments for the Qu'ran being true) over many centuries, so using that argument for the Bible makes no sense.  How do you know the Bible is the truth?  To answer that question, you cannot start out assuming the Bible is true, then use it to discount other beliefs.  You have to show what it is about the Bible that makes it believable.  If most scholars are right and the gospels are not eyewitness accounts and were written *after* Paul wrote his letters and epistles which shaped the doctrine of the church, what argument exists to believe the accounts written in the gospels?  What about the fact that some of the gospel writers copied from others and changed certain details?  These are the kinds of things that bother me, and that I have never been able to find reasonable explanations for.  I know much of this is based on faith--but I can't just turn my brain off when it comes to these issues.  I don't need proof of everything I believe--but I do need it to be reasonable, and I do need to know there is not strong evidence to the contrary.  Does that make sense?<br>
<br>
Thanks for the invitation to e-mail you.  I appreciate your honesty and your efforts here, I might take you up on it sometime.  <br>
<br>
